e prepared to view them for the entire week.	
Mar 20 2007 	Not the Ritz but hard to beat for just a few quid!	The Hotel Columbus is located in a vibrant area of Paddington/Bayswater, off of Sussex Gardens (a very active hotel street) very close to Paddington station and the Lancaster Gate tube stop. The front desk staff is very welcoming and friendly, and the continental breakfast that is included in the price was superb. We had to book an additional night on short notice because our flight was cancelled, but they worked with us and gave us a good price, but make sure they give you whatever is quoted on the website; there's no reason to pay rack rate. FYI, they do provide wi-fi connection (when it works), but like more and more places, they charge for this convenience, and it was 2 GBP/hour. The rooms were small and cozy, but comfortable. The bathroom was functional, albeit cramped. The stairs were also snug, particularly for big football player-sized guys like me, especially for the third (fourth to us yanks) floor, but one finds this all over Europe, really. All in all, you'll be hard pressed to find a better place to drop your bags and crash, and enjoy a quick shower and breakfast in the morning, than the Columbus. It may not be luxury, but chances are if you're reading this, you're not looking for 5 stars and 300 GBP to pay a night for a bed, either.	
Oct 19 2006 	ok but beware the stairs	nice location near Paddington (Heathrow express), decent sized room, comfortable bed. Nice fresh air with the window open, but lots of street noise, so beware if you are sensitive to this. Ear plugs should do the trick.. Reasonably clean, the usual tiny shower etc for a room of this price.Biggest problem: lots of narrow stairs. 2nd floor in the UK means 3rd floor in the US. Ouch!! if you are carrying lots of bags. Other than that, only complaint is noisy neighbors who insisted on slamming their door shut with a big bang. A few words with them, however, produced a noticeable improvement.	
Jul 30 2006 	excellent value for money	Five of us stayed here for a weekend in London. The location was fabulous, just 5 minutes walk from Paddington Station.Let's face it, when you are taking a short break in our capital city, the last thing you want to do is waste time in your hotel! All you need is a safe base, with clean rooms and a shower to go back to - and that's what the columbus hotel is. It's not luxury, no. But if you just need a place to stay, in a great location then this is it. The staff were friendly, the continental breakfast was adequate and the rooms were clean and sufficient. The only complaint we would have is that it was powerfully hot in London when we stayed and there is no AC in the rooms. There were fans, but nevertheless it was still a bit too hot. Overall, excellent value for money.	
Jun 6 2006	Delightful hybrid of historic and modern	The Columbus is in a small, Edwardian-era townhouse, with room size and stairways reflecting those origins. The decorators have made optimal use of the space, however, and the furnishings are handsome, simple and useful.My husband, child and I found that we had adequate space, though my recollection is that the bathroom door interfered with the desk space--this may not be an ideal choice for businesspeople.I *loved* the bathroom--it suggested something that you would find on a spaceship. Very small, but so clean and bright and ingeniously organized. It is true that the shower simply cannot be contained, and most of the bathroom contents will get wet during use.The stairs are rather narrow and steep, but well-lit and, like the rooms, having a very high ceiling; heavy luggage may prove unwieldy for some. That said, the proprietors were very gracious about tending ours after our checkout so we could have the day for sightseeing.The staff were always courteous, charming and helpful.We found the location of the hotel extremely convenient. It's only a couple of blocks from Hyde Park, and surrounded by any number of not just restaurants but also food shops to allow you to assemble your own picnic for the park.We had two significant complaints about the hotel: like the majority of homes and small hotels in England, it doesn't have air conditioning, and August of 2003 was HOT. And I'm speaking as a Virginian. When we left the door of the room open, we got a decent cross-draft from the large window--but that was hardly an option for overnight! The staff let us use the fan from the reception area after it closed, but they only had one, so I don't know what other guests did! And while Sussex Gardens looks like a negligible little side street on a map, it turns out to be EXTREMELY busy, all night long, and the terraced buildings just funnel the noise up to the window. Otherwise, I liked the hotel very much; I enjoyed feeling integrated into London life and I felt the staff genuinely cared about my comfort and happiness. If you are relatively fit and prefer to spend your time, energy, and money enjoying the sights, sounds, and unique offerings of London rather than your hotel room, I think you could be delighted with the Columbus.	
